claim.claim-text:
An optical code scanner (110) comprising:
a base housing (200) defining a belt aperture (210) in which a conveyor belt (225) is mounted, and defining an upper surface (205);
an upper housing (230) extending upwards from the upper surface (205), and including an image capture device (235) mounted therein and directed to cover a field of view above the upper surface (205);
an imaging scanner (305) operable to decode barcodes from an image captured by the image capture device (235).

A method implemented by a computer in an optical code scanner (110), the method comprising the steps of:
(a) receiving an item presented to the scanner (110) for identification;
(b) causing a conveyor belt (225) disposed in the scanner (110) to move the item through the field of view of at least one of a plurality of image capture devices (235 or 265);
(c) capturing at least one image of the item as it moves through the field of view;
(d) processing the captured at least one image to decode data for an optical code captured in the image;
(e) causing the conveyor belt (225) to move the item off of the scanner (110) on the side (220) opposite the side (255) it was received on when all processing is complete.

The method of claim 9, further including the steps of:
(d.3)after step (d.1), upon determining no optical code data was decoded, determining if the item has been rescanned at least once;
(d.4)after step (d.3), upon determining the item has not been rescanned, performing the steps of:
(d.5) reversing the direction of the conveyor belt (225);
(d.6)after step (d.5), determining the item has reached the scan area of the scanner (110) and stopping the conveyor belt (225); and
(d.7)after step (d.6), repeating steps (b)-(d).

The method of claim 10, further comprising the steps of:
(d.8)after step (d.3), upon determining the item has been rescanned at least once, performing the steps of:
(d.9) stopping the conveyor belt (225);
(d.10) after step (d.9), sending a message requesting a cashier identify the item;
(d.11) after step (d.10), receiving a command to continue;
(d.12) after step (d.11), starting the conveyor belt (225).

The method of claim 10, further comprising the steps of:
(d.1)after step (d),transmitting the decoded data on an external peripheral bus;
(d.2) after step (d.1), receiving a command to weigh the scanned item;
(d.3) after step (d.2), stopping the conveyor belt (225);
(d.4)after step (d.3), determining the weight of the scanned item on the conveyor belt (225) using a weigh scale (270) in the scanner (110) where the conveyor belt (225) is mounted on the weigh scale (270);
(d.5)after step (d.4),transmitting the weight of the item on the external peripheral bus; and
(d.6)after step (d.5), starting the conveyor belt.

The method of any of claims 8 to 12, further comprising the steps of:
(b.1) receiving an input from a foot pedal device (165);
(b.2) after step (b.1), determining the input is a command to stop the conveyor belt and stopping the conveyor belt (225).
